{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":88729,"duration_api_ms":88720,"num_turns":17,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"95add6c9-940d-48b6-beae-8f3cc77fea8e","total_cost_usd":0.46166950000000007,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":33695,"cache_read_input_tokens":322582,"output_tokens":3043,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":33695,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":10,"outputTokens":3043,"cacheReadInputTokens":322582,"cacheCreationInputTokens":33695,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.44800975000000004,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":10,"outputTokens":693,"cacheReadInputTokens":25735,"cacheCreationInputTokens":6089,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.013659750000000002,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Evaluated 5 amendments against the codebase. Two amendments (fr-8-f881e1e1 and fr-8-19d961a9) identify concrete, actionable bugs where tmux adapter behavior diverges from process_backend in ways that violate stated acceptance criteria. Two amendments (fr-8-5aba0f56 and fr-8-d2366c9b) identify real but low-severity edge cases that are mitigated by existing safeguards. One amendment (fr-8-63eaddd6) is a documentation-only suggestion about semantic differences in timeout enforcement.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-8-5aba0f56","decision":"accept","rationale":"The race is real: after the timeout fires, the io_and_wait future (holding pipe handles) is dropped at match-arm exit, but spawn_background_reap has already been called with the cloned Arc<ManagedChild>. The SIGKILL sent by force_kill() will terminate the child, but the background reap's wait() could theoretically stall briefly until the OS finishes draining pipes. On Linux, SIGKILL ensures the child dies promptly so the pipe write-ends close, making this a narrow window in practice. However, explicitly dropping the pipe handles before spawning the reap task is a straightforward fix that eliminates the race entirely, and the timeout path is now exercisable by design. Worth fixing."},{"amendment_id":"fr-8-d2366c9b","decision":"accept","rationale":"The analysis is correct: attempt=0 causes saturating_sub(1) to underflow to u32::MAX, then saturating_pow saturates the multiplier, producing a 60s delay (the cap) instead of the expected 0s. While attempt=0 'shouldn't happen' (attempts are 1-indexed), the type system doesn't prevent it, and a defensive guard is trivial (one line). The 60s cap prevents catastrophic behavior, but producing 60s backoff for a non-existent 0th attempt is a latent correctness bug. The fix is simple and makes the function robust against misuse."},{"amendment_id":"fr-8-63eaddd6","decision":"reject","rationale":"This is a documentation-only suggestion about semantic differences between reqwest's timeout and process-level SIGKILL. The analysis is accurate — reqwest timeout may fire late during slow streaming — but the system already handles this correctly: the service-level safety-net at request.timeout + 30s catches any late adapter timeout. The 30s buffer being 'wasted' in streaming scenarios is not a bug; it's acceptable overhead for the common case. The existing code comments at service.rs:204-208 already explain the buffer rationale. Adding more documentation about reqwest internals provides marginal value and doesn't identify a defect that needs fixing."},{"amendment_id":"fr-8-f881e1e1","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a clear bug. The process_backend has classify_exit_failure() (line 1466-1471) that maps exit code 127 to FailureClass::BinaryNotFound (terminal, no retry), but the tmux adapter at line 564-585 unconditionally maps all non-zero exits to FailureClass::TransportFailure (retryable up to 5 times). This means a 'command not found' error in tmux mode wastes retry attempts on an unrecoverable failure. The retry policy explicitly marks BinaryNotFound as terminal (retry_policy.rs:57), so the tmux adapter's hard-coded TransportFailure bypasses this design. The fix is straightforward: reuse or replicate classify_exit_failure() in the tmux adapter's error path."},{"amendment_id":"fr-8-19d961a9","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a resource leak bug. The tmux adapter's invoke() method (lines 519-598) calls prepared.cleanup() and prepared.finish() only after wait_for_session_exit() returns. When the service-level timeout fires (service.rs:223-228), tokio::select! aborts the invoke future mid-flight, so prepared.cleanup() never runs. The cancel() method (tmux.rs:601-658) cleans up the tmux session and calls session.cleanup(), but never calls prepared.cleanup() or prepared.preserve_failed_artifacts(). This leaks Codex/OpenRouter temp files (schema and message JSON files described at process_backend.rs:55-90) and skips the failed-artifact preservation that would aid debugging. The process_backend handles this correctly in its timeout path. The tmux adapter's cancel() needs to receive and clean up the PreparedCommand."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"36beba01-7cc6-481c-bbdb-74b81369ecaf"}
